\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Now, you were born in 1895?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 1895.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Whereabouts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Wolstanton, New Street, Wolstanton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What sort of district?
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\s15\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid8065831 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 The poorest street in the place; yes, the poorest of the lot. And roughest.
\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid8065831 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs24\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang2057\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What kind of house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Terrace-type of house: two bedrooms, a two-bedroomed house, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What was there downstairs? Scullery and kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Just front room, er, the kitchen and what we called the scullery, stood off at the back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What had you in your scullery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh, nothing much there, you know mother's washtub and just a sink. A mangle, of course, about the only
 thing that we had. Electric was out of the question. Even gas was out of the question.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What sort of lighting had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes, paraffin lamps, yes; no gas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Had you a kitchen range, a stove, or what?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, it was a kind of - no, it wasn
't a range, it was an old fashioned grate. You did your cooking in front of the fire in one of those that we call a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15685148\charrsid13830126 D}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
utch oven. That's where you did your cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How about heating water?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Water? Of course, you had to boil a kettle or - or - saucepan, no heating at all in any way, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Was your front room used only on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Was your front room used only on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, that was a out the only day not normally, unless someone called, when relatives called or someone
 like that, you see, and when my father died of course the relatives didn't seem to cling to you too well, it was a case of what we used to term soldier on and do the best you can. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How many brothers and sisters had you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Um, we had four fune
rals in six months; my eldest brother died in July, Father died in the September, Mother was confined in the October and my sister was buried on the Boxing Day. That's how things were. My mother married again 1907, I was about 11 then. She married again..
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What was your father's job?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
He worked in a brickyard, making bricks. Now, as far as I know, there wasn't a machine to make bricks, they were all made by hand. The machines came out later, but my father was a brickmaker. And it was considered a
 fairly good trade, you knew, but he died of pneumonia which was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 scourge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
 then in 1900; when you got pneumonia in those days you died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Have you any memories of your father at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, I can't say that I have. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 Knowing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  that he died, he used to, he was a sporting man, he was in a drum and fife band. He had a kettle-drum, he had a piccolo and he had a gun and he also had a terrier. Of course where Wolstanton Colliery is now there was the 
\{blank\} road? There were a few rabbits and my father used to shoot rabbits, but personally I couldn't, no, only from the photograph that my mother had; I couldn't, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No did your mother make ends meet, then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Hard work and nothing else. My mother never had a rug, she never had a carpet on her floor; my mot
her's stairs were as white as snow and the bedroom, my mother did. She always said nothing beats soap and water and elbow grease. My mother was a character and she was one of the cleanest women alive, my mother was. When she worked for Sidney Barnes, he u
s
ed to play in test matches in 1909, my mother always washed his flannels. He didn't go to a laundry. She was one of the finest washer-women that ever lived in this part of the world. She used to say soap and water and elbow grease will do anything and she
 was like a machine when she would go charring all day, bring some washing home with her, and myself, my sister, we used to go out and fetch washing in and that was what she would be doing after she'd been out all day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 So she did people's washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes. I walked from here to bottom of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Red Street
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, top end of? \{blank\} myself, sister, fetched washing in, mother had washed it, we'd to take it back, had to walk every inch of the way. There was no Dimsdale then past the sanatorium, up that way. When 
I was old enough to, when I left the colliery, I went to Banley big pit, come to work at the brickyard. I had to walk it, get up at six in the morning you now, and we had to walk in all weathers. Oh yes, there was no riding at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Would you tell your mother at all apart from Saturday morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes the days my mother used to go out charring and my sister I told you about did the housework and my mother used to go \{BLANK\}
 my sister was two years older than me, when she left school she had to start work of course, my brother worked at the old brickyard down here. I'd have to cook his dinner meat \{BLANK\}
 I'd to cook that, dinner hour at school was twelve to two, I'd have to cook his dinner, take it to the brickyard over there, come back and wash the d
ishes. When I came out of school at half past four I couldn't stay playing with other lads, I'd have my kitchen floor to do, and the first thing that mother used to say when she came home, she used to "Look in the corner" ha ha, and you know, I couldn't g
o
 out in the street and lay unless I asked my mother, "Can I go out?", "Yes, but don't go out of the street, I may want you to run errand", she was so full of work, her time was so fully occupied and I daren't go out of the street - if I weren't there when
 she called me, I'd had it!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were you punished often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, oh yes, \{BLANK\}
 as hard as and in that street, of course there was a bit of spare land and I liked a ball game, there wasn't a ball, we used to make the ball up with old rags and string a
nd play with that. Well you know how you get, I used to wander off. When I used to come along the entry into the street where I lived, I used to say to the first lad, "Has my mother been calling of me?" And if she had I'd know I was for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 She was strict with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Oh, yes. She was so strict that if she said something like "Look here, go so-and-so." I hadn't to give her what you'd call a black look. I got one first and then I used to rumble what it was for. She says "I'll give you black looks!" Oh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Was she strict over bedtime?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Yes, oh yes. As a lad I couldn't go out in the street, when she thought it was bed time. "Johnnie" it was and upstairs I'd go. I've been to many a house, begged a pair of shoes. Anyone that she thought, someone wh
o'd had a new pair of shoes. Once when she was working for Mrs. Harris along {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Second Avenue{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 at Porthill they had a servant come from ales. My mother did a lot of charring for Mrs. Harris. Every Saturday morning I used to go to Mrs. Harris' to fetch a big br
ead pudding the cook made, used to make from the crusts you know. And Mary used to come to our house on a Wednesday evening, it was her night out and her home was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
Wales{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, she couldn't go. She used to come to me mothers, on Saturday mornings I'd go down fetch this bread pudding. And glad we were of it too.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were you well fed or were you sometimes hungry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I never had too much, as a youngster, oh no. Never had too much, rough, but never as I say really we went }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 hungry}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 , but there have been times when I've been glad to get a bit of bread and butter, bit of treacle, or jam, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Would you have meat on a Sunday or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, she would have a bit of meat on Sundays. She used to get it from a foreign butchers shop in the village,
 the very cheapest she could buy. Breast of mutton, 3d. a pound then. You could get the best joint 7d, 8d. a pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I do remember this, my Aunt at Chesterton was working on the brickyard and of course you never came to our house unless my mother was 
washing, and this aunt came here this day and she said "Before I'd do this - \{BLANK\}
 Come and work for me on the brick yard, brushing these quarries, these red quarries, come and work with me." We went to live in Chesterton in a little cottage, the cottage
 was just a little living-room, a little scullery and no back way out, and the back wall came right up to the brick yard; the light was shut out almost by ridges and tiles. They were stacked. She went to work with this Aunt at this brickyard and when the 
man found out she had started to work on a brickyard he stopped her a shilling and a loaf.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 So you weren't much better off?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No. we had to apply to the Board of Guardians, used to sit at Chell workhouse. She knew the Registrar because as I say we'
d had four deaths in six months and the Clerk of the Guardians was the Registrar. She applied and she went to Chell and before she went, said to my aunt, she put us the best we'd got on, "If I don't get what? It will be a van, we're all going in. So look 
after them 'till I come back. She came back, I always remember Mother saying that the Chairman of the Guardians said it never ought to have been done, they never knew anything at all about it. I well remember Mother saying that this Mr. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 Bassett}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 , I always re
member the name, gave her half a crown and said "Go and get yourself, Mrs. Glover, go get your children something to eat". This man had done it on his own, and years later this man got nine months for robbing women and children, \{BLANK\}
 the same thing, he got nine months, they were a well-known family but he got nine months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 So how long was your mother working at the brickyard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Very very little, it couldn't have been very long because we only lived at Chesterton ten months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And you came back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
She came back to Wolstanton, she couldn't do with Chester-ton, yet as a girl she was born at Chesterton; she used to say "It's the last hole that God ever made, he never finished it". But we came back here, it was the same old game, charring. Then 
when we went to Chesterton for this short period this was where she found the man who she eventually married him, because he lived about two doors away, that's how things happened.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Have you ever had a garden in any of these houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, I never 
lived in a house with a garden; no. when I came to live here I took two allotments on but I never lived in a house with a garden.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 When your father died, had you any help at all from friends or relatives or were you more or less left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh no, left
, left. My mother, she had a little bit of club money, of course, she tried a little shop but that failed, but she had to carry on with the charring, but I will say this, that this old joiner asked me mother to go to work for Mrs. Barnes, it was the best 
thing ever happened to my mother. Charring and cleaning but he was a good friend to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 He was a good man?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes, he was a good man to her. Do you know what charring was then for a woman, a day's work? Do you know what some of these women were 
paid. These people were master potters, one and six a day. My mother used to get two shillings and half a crown at Mrs. Barnes, these others used to get eighteen pence for a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 She was very fortunate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Very, but she earned every penny and of co
urse Mrs. Barnes realised this and so did Mr. Barnes. And once, when a friend of my mother used to go charring, she was ill, she wouldn't go to one of these master potters. She asked me mother to go in her place, she did a good hard days work, when it com
e to time for going home the lady gave her eighteen pence. She said "What's this? I don't work for eighteen pence where I work for I got two shillings, half a crown, that's no good to me". She gave her another sixpence.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Was your mother ever ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, I don't think so. She was a very powerful woman, a very powerful woman. She couldn't afford to be. She never was ill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 (Mother died 1942 aged 78.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Therefore born 1864.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Therefore 31 when Mr. Glover born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Therefore 36 when first husband died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Therefore 43 when remarried)
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Had she any outside interests when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
None, none whatever. She did like a drink of beer, but only what you might say the two half-pints. She, wouldn't afford any more, but she had no interests at all, no, well she hadn't time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Not even Chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Pardon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What about the Chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Well, as children we had to go; there was no argument. And my elder brother after leaving school, he was in the choir but I had to go until I was about fifteen. I suppose as boys get bigger they didn't want to go.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Had you any Sunday School outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Outings? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 
We had a kind of Sunday School treat, we went to Congleton, and of course if you went, same as Trentham, you had to walk there and back
 again, there was a way that, on August Bank Holiday originally, some boats on the canal at Burslem, you could go to Trentham for twopence or threepence but I hadn't twopence at that age. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
I've gone to Burslem many a time to the pawn brokers, for neighbours
, gone to Burslem cost they could get threepence or sixpence more there than in the village. I've come back and of course walked it. I've had a penny, I've had to turn that penny up. I worked all week, stay at home cleaning, used to get halfpenny on Satur
day and if my mother felt I was doing well, it would be penny on Saturday, that was me reward (laughter). Now what I am telling you is the honest truth. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How old were you when you started schooling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Three.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Whereabouts was the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Up in the village there, Church of England by the Church there, started at three then in what we called the Infants.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were the boys and girls separate or were they mixed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Boys and girls were separate, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How big a school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Well, Miss, I really couldn't say how many there were; same school is used now mind you, there was a large room for the girls of course and two classrooms and the boys, there was a large room and two classrooms - possibly about the same number of boys and
 girls, but I couldn't really say what numbers there were, you know, but about the same girls as boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How did you like school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Didn't like it at all. Didn't like it at all. I was always leaned to ball games, I played cricket for Porthill, someth
ing like that, football of course. I used to like billiards as I grew up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were they strict with you at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes, very. I was glad to leave school; yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And you left school and started working when?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I left school and went to a bu
tcher's shop, you see, I left when I was twelve when I should have gone till I was thirteen. But owing to this mistake -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How did you manage this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I don't know, I'm sure I don't, just through my mother, really. She kind of talked me into this thi
ng and anyway I had no difficulty but I couldn't go in a factory }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 'cos}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
 I'd need a birth certificate, see, and I went to the little butcher's shop until I was thirteen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Who found it for you, this job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 The butcher's shop? Well, probably my mother;
 I wouldn't know. Of course, it wasn't far from home, you see, in the same village, and then at the end of six months another shop had opened in the village, another foreign shop, there wasn't trade enough for one foreign shop, people were prejudiced agai
n
st foreign meat, and then this one opened at the other end and our shop closed and the business was transferred to Newcastle. Well, I had to go to Newcastle, to this shop in Newcastle to look after the customers at Wolstanton. So I had to walk to Newcastl
e and then come back from Newcastle to bring the orders out, round here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What sort of work was it in fact, or taking orders only?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Just taking the orders out, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How much were you paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Five bob a week; yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What sort of hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I used to get down there at about {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 30}}
{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 8}}}half past eight{\*\xmlclose}, leave there probably -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were they decent employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes, yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And you left there after a year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, you see, I went in a brickyard: there was more money you see. At the
 butchers shop is was only five bob, at the brickyard it was six bob. I worked a lot harder, but that shilling counted.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes. The shilling counted, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What were you doing at the brickyard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Well, they'd got a machine there
 that made tiles, these tiles'd be flowing out here and as they came off the I was a catcher, catching them, putting them in bundles slide 'em along a bit and make another bundle, that's how you were all day sometimes he'd find me another job riddling cin
d
ers from the ovens or something like that. They would use some of the sheds where they dry the tiles or summat, various jobs like that, you know, then when I was fourteen I was itching to be fourteen, cost the colliery worked short hours you see and I got
 a bit more money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How big a concern was the brickworks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Well, it as owned by one man, and he was a distant relative of ours, a half-cousin, you might say, of my mother. He eventually turned out to be the, owner, I would say, the biggest tile-maker in the world; that was E.H.Downing }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9206880 &}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
 Co., you have probably seen the name, well Harry Downing who owned the firm then, and he had had luck over there and then he went to Chesterton, he grew, grew, grew to be the biggest tile-maker in the world, but she 
got no help from him, not from him, and while I was working on this job catching and riddling cinders, chap came from office, I had to go Downing's house at Chesterton fetch his dinner, he'd be at the works, I had to walk there and back, of course.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 You were fourteen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I left there at fourteen, I did a few weeks at Hanley Big }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16524950\charrsid13830126 P}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 it on the screens there, nine shillings a week there, I got the sack there for nothing much really. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 
I suppose it was according to the times, but the first hour in the mornin
g the screens did nothing hardly as the underground men were travelling, nothing comes up the pit you see the first hour, and me and another young man we'd got to clean some benches, rubbish, so this lad he had a pack of cards, they were only a penny a pa
ck then and we'd nothing to do at the moment, we were waiting for stuff to come up, he said "I've a pack of cards, which will you have?" }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
The surface manager came down some steps and he saw us with these cards, we were doing no harm at all but he was furious
, sent us both off. I came home, my mother had married again in the meantime, I came up the yard with my clogs on, I had those clogs on you know, to the door, she heard my clogs in the yard "What's up?" I said "I've got the sack". "What! I wish I'd have b
e
en down those stairs. Get out! Get out, and another job before you get home, before you come home" and you can believe me, I dared not come home. I walked to Chesterton, I'd already walked to Hanley and back, I walked to Chesterton, called on this brickya
r
d on my way, and I started to work at twelve o'clock and I worked till six and I was glad to start, I was glad to start, and as I came home I'd got my food with me as I'd taken to Hanley, as I came up the yard towards seven at night before I got to the ho
use, remember we'd got a yard, "Have you got a job? It's a good job, you have."
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I worked there for three weeks, then I went on pit bank, stuck to colliery work then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Was it very easy to find a job then
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, no, no. It so happened that this 
step-father of mine, he was working on the pitbank and I think one of the boys had been driving one of the horses and he'd gone to work in the pit, you see, and they wanted a lad to drive a horse and he got me the job. I was on the pitbank sometime till e
ventually I got to work in the pit with my elder brother are of course I remained there until nineteen thirty. I didn't stay at that colliery, I've been from Parkhouse to H \{BLANK\} H? \{BLANK\}
 to Wolstanton. And eventually I thought I would try for something
 better. I went to night school, I learnt to be a fireman, a deputy. And in nineteen twenty-eight, nineteen twenty-eight, I became what we call a shaft-minder/winder and two months afterwards I was made a fireman and in 1930 or 31 I think it was I was in 
charge of a biggish job, in command, well me boss asked me to come out onto the surface, he had a job that was flagging, he wanted some drive in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And what were you earning when you first started at the pit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 When I first went on to the pit I got nine shillings a week, yes, nine shillings a week, I got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What sort of hours was that
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Er, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 54}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour
}{\xmlattrvalue 13}}}six till two{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname time}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Minute}{\xmlattrvalue 54}}{\xmlattr\xmlattrns0{\xmlattrname Hour}{\xmlattrvalue 13}}}six till two{\*\xmlclose}
, no six till half-past two, half-past two, because there was a strike in 1912, we got the half hour knocked off, and you'd hardly credit it, but the local Owners wanted us to work through without any food time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 It wasn't much better.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Well, we got twenty minutes for food time, which remains that now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Breakfast was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, twenty minutes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 A meal when you got home then
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Oh yes, yes. They allowed us twenty minutes and we had to fight for that, oh yes, yes, and they knocked that half hour off. It was six till two, it used to be half past two, we worked right through and it remained at that twenty min
utes in the collieries ever since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were you involve in unions or politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
No, I can't say that I have. I've always been a Union man. In fact, I wouldn't, if I were an employer of labour, I wouldn't employ a man unless he was a member of a union.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
There's been no good old days. You've heard people talk of the good old days but there's never been any for working men. There's never been any good old days at all. The only way that things have grown as they have has been through
 the strength of the Unions. If I was an employer of labour today, knowing what I know, what I've seen, I couldn't employ a man unless he was in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Union{\*\xmlclose}
, because it's only been the strength of the Unions. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 I've always been a labour man and I've always bel
ieved in giving a really good day's work for a day's pay and I've been congratulated many a time on the work that I've done on a day wage but its only been the unions that's brought the country to what the workers are today. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I'm afraid they're going above it now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, I'm afraid they are; yes. Only the strength of the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Union{\*\xmlclose}
 that brought them from what they were in my days. Without the Unions they could do nothing. In the early days well when a man was sacked he was sacked, that were it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were the employers decent or not;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Some were, some weren't; you couldn't do enough for some; some could be slave-drivers, you know, and some couldn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I suppose you stayed at home after your mother re-married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, I didn't marry }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 till}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  I w
as 27. Of course, I joined the Army at 19 one-half and I was, you see, I did three years and ten months, I did just two months short of the four years in the Army, then that trade depression which they were saying we'd make Germany pay, collieries shut do
wn, then the strike in 1921, work a week, play a week, and I got married in 1922, I was 27; May, 1922, I was 27 when I got married, Mrs. Glover was 26, we had no money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Had you known your wife a long while
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I'd known her all my life, known her all
 my life. We didn't play together as children, mind you, but I'd known her; I'd known her family I'd known the family like all my life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How did it work, was it awkward having a stepfather round the place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, I won't say that it was, because as
 I say, my mother was a very strong-willed person, she was the gaffer, ha ha! She was the gaffer, she feared no-one, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 After you started work had you much social life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, I played cricket at Porthill. I was possibly the only working man i
n the team at one time, you know, one of the scruffs, about twelve years, up to the age of 40, then I felt I'd had enough. I played football quite a lot, I've been a good mixer I think. Made plenty of friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were your friends local?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 Oh yes, but some as playing cricket, Nantwich, or we, going to visit you do make friends.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Well, we had eight children, we lost, me mother had, we lost three in five months, and we had lost one before then altog
ether we had a family of eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Your eldest brother died in 1900 and your sister died in 1900 as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes, yes. July, September and on the Boxing Day, that is quite true.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And your eldest sister was about -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 My eldest sister is two years older than I am, in fact she is in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
Street}}London Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} now, I am going down to see her tonight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And how much older was your elder brother than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I had two older brothers, but one died at the time in 19 - one died then, and me other brother was killed. \{BLANK\} Run over \{BLANK\}
 motor cycle. In '62. He was eight years older than I, he would have been 81 he would have been 82 come April, that is 19 nineteen years ago, he was killed, motor cycle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 You said, would you know how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Yes, my father, a funny thing, I have heard my father say he was 40 and I heard an uncle say he was 41, I was 5 when me father died, so my father would be roughly 35 or 36 you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And had he always been a brickmaker in Hanley?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And did he ever have any casual or part time jobs at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, no part time at all. Well you see their job then was 12 hours, 6 in the morning until 6 at night you see, on brick yards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Was he ever out of work at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Only, I would 
remember, I had to go by what mother told me, what really happened I believe, and I have heard other people say this, that it would be before 1900 of course, there was a 13 weeks frost, now brickyards couldn't work when there was frost. And I have heard m
e
 mother say that there was 13 weeks frost and he did nothing whatever. But I have heard other people talking, older people talking about that 13 weeks frost, but as for being out of work I really couldn't say, but there was 13 weeks then that they did no 
work, when they had a severe frost you see. You can't make clay bricks with frosted in clay you see, so I understood then that they had a tremendous time you now with this 13 weeks frost.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Did your mother work at all before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes, she was a servant at a public house. You know, what we call the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 
skivvies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 , you know, cleaning, sort of, at a public house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 You mean general maid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, at a public house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And you said that she worked a fair amount after your father died at inns, charring -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 When she was working did he have anybody to look after you or were you all at school by that time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, well of course we had to look after ourselves you see until she married again. My elder brother started to wo
rk of course, he was 8 years older than me, and he worked at the brickyard, I'd have to come home and get him a bit of dinner ready, I used to work a bit of bacon and cheese, or bacon and egg, take it in and come back again. Me sister was 2 years older th
an me when she started to work of course I had to do}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
kind of the housework, take her place, that's how I followed on you see, and me mother continued to work for, oh even after she'd married again, she used to go out charring and bringing washing home and like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 So you look after yourself a fair bit as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 We had to look }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 after ourselves}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 , oh yes we did a lot, yes, a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 When you moved back to Wolstanton after you had left Chesterton, what sort of a house was this that you moved into, how big was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
The house we came into? Just an ordinary terraced house, two bedrooms, two bedrooms, the same as the one below this, this is a three bedroom and the bottom one is a three bedroom and the others are two bedroom and a parlour and a ki
tchen and then there was a kind of what we used to term a back kitchen, where you had, where you did the washing at the sink, stood off a little bit from the house you know, just an ordinary two bedroom dwelling house you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And there weren't ever any other people, either relatives or lodgers, living with you at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Would your mother always spend a certain part of the day on doing the housework? Did she do certain things on certain days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, I don't think she ever had a set
 day because, well, of course when she was a char, until she got married again, she might have had a couple of days of week after she married, well of course when she married again and they had a family again}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 most of her time was occupied in the house, of course, but she used to go to Sidney Barnes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16524950\charrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 twice a week, she'd go whenever Mrs. Barnes wanted her really you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Would your mother make your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Well she had used to do, when we were smaller children of course, she kind of made us somethi
ng out of someone else's and all like that you know. She'd perhaps set a coat off someone, and probably make me a pair of trousers out of something like that you know or perhaps beg a jacket of off someone or something like that you know really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What sort of things would you help your mother with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 
Well I tell you what she'd do, after me father died, she'd opened a little shop but that seemed to fail, then she tried her hand at baking oatcakes at the weekend, and she used to start about midnight, 
oh she only did it on Saturday nights and Sundays, she started at midnight on Saturday night and she'd bake up to perhaps 11 o'clock on Sunday morning you know a memorable thing is someone had got her a plate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16524950\charrsid13830126 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126  a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16524950\charrsid13830126 Baxter,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8206966\charrsid13830126 
 a square steel plate you know, I don
't know where she got that from, but I had to scrounge some bricks from anywhere where there was spare land, a remarkable thing, I've even been collecting mud, me mother built her own fireplace, put the steel plate on the Baxter(?) you call it you know, a
