I think, well, I think me mother left home when she was 12 she ran away from home, she was born at Chesterton, she hated Chesterton, I don't know anything of me grandparents there, 
but I understand that she left Chesterton when she was 12 and came to this pub and became a servant. Ah. And she stayed at the pub I think until she was married. But. From the age of 12 shall we say, I don't know what happened before then, from the age of
 
12 until she was married she'd had to kind of fight her own way and look after herself, hold her own, shall we put it that way, and it must have made her very hard. And I've heard her say the fights that she's witnessed in these pubs when made her a hard 
w
oman. But all through her life she was a very hard woman. Mind you, she'd got a love for her family, but that temper that she had! Tremendous!. You didn't have to wait to be warned before you got a bit of a bat (?) or something like that you got it first.
 You got it first. And that's how she was. Very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970093\charrsid13830126 ,very}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
 hot tempered. If you'd have come to my mother's door perhaps, the same as you've come today, and knock at the door, my mother would come to the door and she might have said to you "Well, what do you want
?" and that's how she'd got, and she didn't make many friends because they never knew what was coming to come you see.
