g like that, oh no, no, oh no. Me mother's life was one large worry from the time me father died until the end of her days as you might say really, because as I say when she got married again things didn't go smooth at all, and as I say before she got mar
r
ied her life was one long drag. And she did think she would improve herself if she got married again but it didn't turn out that way, oh no. No, she'd never kind of give us any, she couldn't give us much advice on what we ought to do and what we ought not
 to do. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970093\charrsid13830126 
We had to kind of do something that would bring a copper in mind you, she was an honest woman, she wouldn't have thieving or anything like that, nothing dishonest, but if you could earn a copper anytime, then you ought to earn a copper and of course
 when you came home you turned it up. I've run an errand many a time for a neighbour to a pawn shop because in those days there were a lot of pawnshops you could get threepence more in Burslem or perhaps sixpence more than what you could the one in the vi
llage. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
I've run to Burslem many a time and taken a bundle of clothing and I've got perhaps sixpence extra for this lady, she'd give me a penny, well I'd turn it up when I got home. Every penny, and every halfpenny. We used to have halfpenny a week }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970093\charrsid13830126 pocket}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  ba
rs but after me sister was at work and I had to do most of the cleaning again. Be a good lad I'll give you a penny on Saturday, and that's all it was, give you a penny and I worked damned hard for that!
