omething occurred there and mother took as away and we went to the one in New Street which of course, that was the Methodist New Connection() they called it, we went to there until I was perhaps got about 16 or so and I suppose the same as big lads do, we
ll I won't go to Sunday School and that was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Did your mother ever attend a chapel at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No. No, I wouldn't say she did really. No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970093\charrsid13830126 
I would say possibly on the very, very rare occasion, very,very rare. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 She might have done, perhaps just the An
niversary Sunday which they do, you know. But apart from that no, her hadn't time. And then of course she hadn't got the smart clothes in many ways you see. She used to keep a bit of a dress she had like, she had a cape in those days, sort of style, that 
she'd had for years, and that had to last. Used to be black, a good many people kept them until they went green almost, until they changed colour. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970093\charrsid13830126 Did you ever attend any other social things organised by the chapel, on a weeknight, or a Band of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6970093\charrsid13830126 Hope or anything like that?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes there was, on Friday nights, Band of Hope. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}
New Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, the New Connection Methodist Chapel, they had one every Friday night they did, we used to go there Friday nights, it was all free mind you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Your brothers and sisters went as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Was your father at all interested in politics, I suppose he died before you were aware of this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, I couldn't say, I couldn't say. I've heard me mother say once, the firm he worked for, at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 Etruria}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
 and something happened, he wanted to open a brickworks in New Zealand, and they wanted me father to go to New Zealand, but me mother wouldn't go, no Mother wouldn't go. No. but so far as Union activities or anything like that, there was very little of i
t done then, the Unions came into their own much later you might say. Very little of it done. Although when I started at it I had to join a (Married?) Miners Federation, well we didn't have to but we joined the (Married) Miners Federation you know. Even t
hat took years and years to work up you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Was your step-father at all interested in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, no, no. He was a Catholic he was. But he never attended any church. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Did your mother ever manage any evenings out, or ever get out and enjoy herself at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
No, No. Only just playing in the street. I was just talking to somebody this week, you see children don't play the games now that we used to do. A bit of game we used to call }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 Relievio,}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  there was marbles you might say, there was a game we used to call Peggy with a stick and a little bit of a \{BLANK\}
 Peggy what they call for? and even now you very rarely see children with skipping ropes do you? Now all these things have gone. That's the only thing as a lad I was interested in football and I had to be careful of that because }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 every time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
 I came in me mother would look at me shoes! And if they were dirty or wearing more than what she thought they ought to wear you know, a damn good hiding. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 
Didn't used to tell me, just a damn good hiding. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
I was passionately fond of football, and cricket as a lad, I always have been really. When I came out of the Army of course I took cricket on and football and all. You know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Did your mother ever manage any evenings out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Not when she was a 
widow, no. but after she married my step-father, as I say, her and me step-father used to go to a public house, on top of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}New Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} there. 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Royal Oak{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And have a drink of beer there. Possibly Saturday night and Sunday night. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 
It wasn't as she drunk a lot, it wouldn't do for me mother to drink a lot after she'd had two-half p}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126 in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 
ts she was ready to fight Jack Johnson}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 
 really it wouldn't do to drink a lot, she was one of those who never should have had it at all, made her work?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Was your mother a member of any savings club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
No, no, never had no - I think I did hear her once say that me father he went in a savings club once and it went smash, but I don't know anything of this. But it might have been for a life policy or something like that, but this club
 smashed up, so me father lost what bit of money he did have in, it couldn't have been a lot, but I remember me mother saying that me father did have some savings in this club but it went smash and he never got anything out of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 When you were still a school child, did you play out your brothers and sisters or were they mostly neighbours children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Always neighbours, neighbours yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Where would you play?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Just in the street, just in the street. The property wasn't as good as this 
or anything like that of course, but just in the street with some of the other boys, you know, get some string and tie it round the paper, and that was our ball, a paper one, we couldn't afford a ball, a paper one, or get an old rag, and tie some string r
ound it, that was our ball, we couldn't afford a ball.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Did your mother mind what children you played with at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, no, oh no, no, no, I think children got on very well together really. Of course, children have their likes and dislikes, but the
re was no kind of discrimination at all then, but of course we never had blacks or anything like that you see, and then, when I was a youngster like that, you know, there was almost as many empty houses as occupied houses, you'd be surprised, at that, oh 
y
es. I've known people move for the sake of threepence and sixpence a week. The house that we lived in, just after me father died, we moved about three times, we moved out of one, it was about 2/9d. a week, that were a general rent, 2/9 d. 3/- a week, and 
w
e went into a three bedroomed house at three and threepence. But you'd be surprised the number of empty houses there were. And these, what they used to call moonlight flits used to take part, you know somebody owed a bit of rent you know, and before they'
d
 pay up, hadn't got the money, they used to move. And of course there were houses standing empty any time. I always remember my mother saying that when she got married she went to live with her mother, with his mother, only a hundred yards away, and they 
kept a coal yard, his mother did. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 
Well she couldn't get on with her mother-in-law, practically nobody got on with me mother, but she couldn't get on with her, and me father had gone to work at Esturia}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126  when he came home me mother had gone, flown, and he had
 to go down Oxford Road there to find out where she'd gone, and she'd gone in a house there that was empty, there, down by the laundry at Oxford Road, had to go down there and find her. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
There was plenty of empty houses.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 You said you had another brother or sister born the same year as your father died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes. Yes. In the October.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Did your mother have any help with this child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 There was no help at all. You see my mother used to get three shillings a week had four loaves of bread. Now the 
bread at that time was a four pound loaf, having a family, she had four leaves of bread, she had three shillings a week. And nothing more. Of course I will say this that neighbours, if they had nothing themselves, neighbours seemed to kind of look after n
eighbours a little bit. Well Mrs. So and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 So's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  a poor soul, and I think I'll do a little bit, that was the feeling then, \{
BLANK\} it doesn't seem as though they have the same feeling now, I don't know why. But neighbours were good to one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Would your mother ever have friends or neighbours who would call in and see her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Just neighbours, yes, a neighbour would call, yes. We had one neighbour at one particular time, she had a big family, same as }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126 we}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  had, but her husband was working, now this chap
 he had a good trade on the pots, he was what they called a turner, but he liked his drink. And very nasty in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126 trouble}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
. But this man would work regular and save, he wouldn't give his wife, save, I remember she used to buy pigs head and make pigs head brew, 
and anything she could possibly do. And then now and again when he's saved and he'd got a bit of brass he used to break out and he'd be weeks, no dole then, no dole then, he'd be weeks, not until he'd spent up and then he'd go to work again. And he'd have
 
a spell like that. And I always remember my mother saying once, and the lady next door told us about it, this chap next door came home, he was drunk, and I say he was very nasty in drink, and he started knocking his wife about, she yelled out, my mother w
e
nt and she feared nothing like that, my mother went in and knocked him down, punched him. Anyway next morning when he got up he felt his face was sore, looked in the mirror, he had a black eye. Said to his wife "Who done this?" She said "Mrs. Glover" I've
 heard me mother say, Mr.\{BLANK\} said "well if she done it I must have asked for it"! They were rough days. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 You have heard that many people split up the pre-1914 period they split the people up into different social groups, would you say this was
 valid? That you could split up people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
There was only two kinds that I remember really, only two kinds, rich and poor you might say. I suppose there was a kind of middle class but a weeks wage then, when I was when I went on the brickyard at thirtee
n, after I left the butchers shop, I couldn't go on a factory until I was 13, a weeks wage then for a full week of 12 hours on the 5 days Monday to Friday 6 to 6 in the evening, then from 6 in the morning until 1 on the Saturday, for a full week was a pou
nd a week. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 
But in the winter time you see, you only worked from half past seven in the morning until half past four, that's what we call three quarter time, so that was a day and a half gone, and that lasted as long as the dark nights lasted, there was no e
lectric lights, we had paraffin lamps, we didn't have gas or anything like that, so if anyone at that particular time, small we say got about 30/- a week, they were kind of middle class people, at that particular time because the labouring wage as I say w
as about a pound. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 So if you got somebody with about 30/- a week, which was 50%, it was a lot of money, ah yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What sort of people were in the same group as you were do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 A lot of them. A lot of them. Different families, generally speak
ing, families had quite big families really, quite big families on the whole. I know two that had 18 children. Old Mr. Jeffreys, he was a window cleaner, had 18 children. And you'd be surprised that he left his wife, in later years, after all these childr
en, and went to live with a young woman up Bucknall \{BLANK\} and \{BLANK\} Mr. Lamb(?)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126 . T}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
hey had 18 children. Biggish families were the rule then, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were you brought up to call people Sir and Madam and this sort of thing, as children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No. We did 
had to know our manners, I will say that, my mother was very strict on that. We never got into company where we had to do that really, because if there was a kind of rare occasion, of course the schoolmaster, we had to call him Sir of course, if there was
 an occasion where it was necessary, we would have to call them sir.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What sort of people would these be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Well it might have been, I don't know exactly, er, it might have been some of these people me mother worked for because she always made us h
ave good manners then in that way and she wouldn't let us, as children, say a miss (?) word to anyone, and she wouldn't let us say a miss word to a neighbour. We daren't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 She was strict about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes, and yet me mother did a lot, oh yes. Nothing vulgar but she used to use a lot of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126 b- with a b-word}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  and that. No, we daren't use cheek to anyone like that, we daren't answer anyone back, oh no, she was very strict on that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 In your area, in Wolstanton say, who was thought of as being the most important people do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Well I don't know that I called anybody as important. I don't think I was brought up to think anyone really important, we had to have respect for some of these people, particularly these people me mother worked for
, and when Sidney Barnes came, me mother always worked for Mrs. Barnes, I respect Sidney Barnes and Mrs. Barnes possible more than anyone else I ever knew. We had to respect the neighbours, we daren't answer them back, we had to have respect for them. But
 as for anybody outstanding I can't say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What about the people like the Minister or the employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Well of course we had to have respect for the Minister, we had to do that of course. But as I say, we had to respect everyone, every grown up. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 Had 
to ------ But we didn't have to kind of cavil to or anything like that. We were never brought up to cavil to anybody really.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What sort of people were the chapel people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Well most of them were working class people of course. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 
There was quite a lot of people then who were non-conformist and they were very, very strictly T.T. and that was always their theme at the chapels of course, of gambling and strong drink and all that you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 But they were mostly working class, there were some with perhaps a little bit better job than the labouring man, let's put it that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were the chapel people rather different from the church going people do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes. Yes. And there was one chapel in the village there, they used to called them the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 Wesleyans}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 , it is {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St. Johns{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}() now, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 Wesleyans}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
. They thought they were different class to the others. They always thought that and I think they acted on that. And the church, of course they were out by themselves they were, but nobody seemed to, well if you were
 a churchman you were a churchman, nobody kind of, bothered. But in chapels there was this kind of jealousy. Same as in New St. where I used to go, I've told you, used to be a very poor church, and I've known people from there who have perhaps picked up t
heir station in use a little bit and they've left and gone to St. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 John's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
! Thought that was a better church you see. And that was the stage between them. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Would you say there was any sort of a difference between the people who were mostly labourers 
and you said that among the working class the labourers and the sort of people who had a better wage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 There was no really good wages. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 
The only people that I know as you might say who had anything of a substantially better wage were these potters, an
d perhaps a manager on a works, a manager on a works, if you term a manager on a works, and some of these pottery people who had these pottery works, and of course they took their own families into it, very much families then, and apart from the manager, 
a
 man who had risen to a manager, there was very little difference between the wages really no. when Sidney Barnes came to Port hill he came in 1906. He came to play cricket at Porthill and he has been the finest bowler the world ever seen, and he came to 
Porthill and his wages were 26 a week as a top class professional, the best there was, 26 a week. But, Mr. Heath}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 
from Biddulph, the old colliery, the ironmasters found him a job that he could work in the week and this was going from siding to siding on the \{ILLEGIBLE\} Railway \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 trucks because Robert Heath owned a lot of trucks, and he only paid him 30 bob a week, and that was supposed to be a good job. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 \{BLANK\}
 It was a job (he was dressed up) and he only got 30 Bob a week. So he did get a good wage, according to what the labouring wage was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 So people who had more wages than 30/- were the different sort from those who had a labouring job at one pound a week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 They thought they were in a different class then, where has always been those kind
 of people, if they thought they were doing a bit better than you, it's always been like that and I think it always will be, it was just the same then, yes, but I don't think you will find it so much now because the level of the wages has risen to such a 
standard now, that even a labourer can get more than what some men that have been well trained in the job can get now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 When you were still a young man though, would you think it was possible to move out of one class into a higher one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, I neve
r thought it would be possible, no I didn't no. I didn't see how I could do it. But I worked in the pits you see, I've done 51 years at a colliery, I did 20 years underground and 30 years on the surface, but I never thought it was possible for me to move 
up, oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Did anybody move up, any of your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 acquaintances}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  or neighbours or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
No, no. Not that I know of, just a couple of odd ones. Been reared in he same street as me but seemed to have, the parents didn't seem to have the trouble that m
y parents had you see, and possibly just a couple of them moved, whose parents could just take a little bit more pride in them in that way, help you know, but generally speaking nobody ever desired in a way, it was a case of had to go to work and earn eve
ry penny you could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 When you were still a schoolboy, did you ever have any contact with the police at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Only once for taking apples! Yes, only once for taking apples, I've never been in trouble. And it was a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 memorable}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126 day}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
, I was only about 14 of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126 us,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  all school lad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126 s. A}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
bout a hundred yards away from the schoolyard, over a wall, there was some apples, and lads you know, we thought there was a very big branch on a tree, so many on this branch which was rather low you know, and grab}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2775243\charrsid13830126  them}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  off you kno
w. The man who lived there was a very (?) on the Council and he got to know these school lads and he informed the police and they came to the school and sorted one or two out and one boy gave the other one away, and one gave the other one, and then this g
entlemen said he wanted to see all the parents. They all went bar my mother, my mother said "You can go up the far end"}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
And I've never been in trouble in any other way. But it fell away you know, nothing was done. But my mother, "I'm not going..." No, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Did you ever see any of your landlords at all? Did you ever have any contact with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
No, no, contact at all, no. One old gentleman used to come for his rent, and in his early days he was a schoolmaster and he took up rent collecting, but I had no contact with them at all really, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 You said your mother applied for help from the workhouse Guardians, what did you feel about this when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Well. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 
Of course I didn't know what she meant you see, I was only about 7 or 8, but I do know this, we'd come to live at Chesterton and me mother got work at a brickyard and they stopped her 3 shilling on a loaf, and she went to Chell, she got to see the Board. 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I always remember seeing the Chairman, a Mr. Bassett, always remember the name
, "Here's half a crown, yourself..." go and get that was before she married again you see. Well that, it didn't disturb me, I don't suppose I was seriously minded enough then as children you know. You're not cut out for that sort of game at that age reall
y.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I suppose it wouldn't affect you so much as you were so young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 No, it wouldn't, no.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Now, you started work when you were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I was 12 really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And you spent a years in a butchers shop in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 Olstanton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 , then you worked at a brickyard, why did you move from the butchers shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Because it was more money, you see I worked at the butchers shop for 6 months, well it closed down, and I was transferred to the shop at Newcastle, I'd been there six months, and I had to bring the meat to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 Olstanton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  because with the business being transferred to Newcastle, I had to bring the meat to these customers at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 Olstanton}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 , until I was 13. I was earning 5 bob a week so you see I went on the brick yard and I was earning 6, and I worked 12 hours for that, th
en eventually-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How did you get your job at the brickyard, did you go and ask for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Oh yes, oh yes, I went to ask for it, yes. It was only 6 shillings a week, then of course I had the sack off that, for a little bit of a thing, it was nothing really, then I worked at the it, at Hanley big pit, and I used to walk to Hanley big pit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 You were sacked because you were playing cards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes. But this brick yard, you've seen these Marl holes, big high, with birds nests I was climbing up, knocke
d off a bit of rock wasn't a shovel full man who looked after the mark hole saw me do it and he told the boss, and I got the sack.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And then you worked at Hanley big pit, and you only stayed there a few weeks?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 That's all, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Then you moved back and worked at another brickyard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How did you get that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
I had to go after it. You see I went to work this morning at Hanley, it was 6 to about 2, half past 2 something like that. It was business, my mother turned us out (?) 
she'd got married in the meantime of course, heard me in the yard in me, clogs, what's up with you? Got the sack. "I wish I'd been down these stairs, I'd give you}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4095630\charrsid13830126 the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 sack! Get out. Don't come home until you get another job!" Well I went down these and wen
t to Chesterton, and I went to about four or five brickyards, and I started at one at 12 o'clock and got me food I'd taken to Hanley, and I started at 12 o'clock and worked 'till 6 and I worked there for a few weeks 'til I went on the pit. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Whereabouts was this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Chesterton.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And you worked on the pit bank did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 That's right, at Parkhouse Colliery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And you stayed there until 1914? When you joined up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Yes, that's right. Then I had to go back, when I came out of the Army,
 I came out of the Army two months before the war finished with malaria you see, and they were short of minors and being a minor I had to go back to the pit again, and I only stayed until about the January, it was very wet. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 So I left Parkhouse and went to Oldridge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 colliery, just changed collieries that's all.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Before you joined up, what sort of job were you doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I was on the ground then, I was on the ground, I went down the pit when I would be about 16 possibly, worked on the surface a couple o
f years and then went down the pit until I'd joined up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Were the wages much better working underground?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Yes, you see on the bank it was 11/- a week, 11/- a week, and when we went in the pit, it would be about 2/9d. a shift, that's six day would 
be 12 bob, 6 nines are 54, that would be about fifteen or sixteen shillings possibly, and that was a rise you see of about four or five shillings. And shorter hours too. And then oh when I would be about 17 I think, used to get threehalfpence a day rise e
v
ery four months, threehalfpence a day, so I was always, I always prided meself anyway on being a good worker, and I'd been doing another chap's job, he'd learnt me to do this job, and this chap used to get 5/- a day, now at this particular time I was gett
ing 3/3d. it had gone up by three }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 halfpence}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
 you see, I was getting 3/3d. and I was due for three halfpence rise, but this chap had learnt me his job, and I used to change him, and he used to get five shilling, I used to change with him you see. Anyway, he l
eft, they put another man in his job, over 21, it had to be 5/- at 21, and he couldn't do the job, well I had to help him out, do me own job, oh what I didn't have to do, and the old man came up and saw me doing it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And this day I went up threehalfpe
nce, I went in the office, and saw the manager like, "Hallo Jack, what do you want?" Well I am entitled to another threehalfpence you know Mr. Green" he said "I'm just talking about you" "Oh" "Yes, "he said "You can do that job can't you, what about havin
g the job?" I said "What for? At 3/3d.? He gets five bob?" "Well" he says "You're not entitled to any more, only this threehalfpence you have come in about see" I said "Expect me to do it for}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4095630\charrsid13830126 
 threequarters, half pence}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 ." he gets five bob. "I'm doing a man's work" So an argument or two "Will you take the job on? Tell you wh}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4095630\charrsid13830126 at}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126  1/2d. I was only \{ILLEGIBLE\} to 3/3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
1/2d. it was a rise really. \{BLANK\} And that's what happened, see I got another 6 bob a week for doing a man's job at 5 bob a day, and I was on that job until I joined up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 I see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 What were the Manager's like, how did you get on with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 
Very well. I pride myself, and I've always done it, I prided myself on trying to be a good workman, and I think I have. I was a Deputy on the pit? Then ... job on the bank}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4095630\charrsid13830126  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 and I've prided myself, like me mother, me mother was as good a workwoman that ever lived, and it must have been bred in me I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 And how did you get on with the other people that you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 All right, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12549552\charrsid13830126 Colliers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4095630\charrsid13830126 , }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 you do more or less, it's a rough life, pretty good pals, oh yes they are.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Did you hand over your wage to your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 Oh yes, oh my word yes! Oh yes. I kept a bit of it, didn't give her it all I didn't let me mother have it all, I kept a bit for 
meself out of it. But I think I let her have half of that shilling a day extra and I think I had the other half, something like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8065831 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 How much spending money would you have all told?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid795538 JG  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 All told, before then, before I had that rise, I used to have 
about eighteenpence, that was all about one and six. But I think I gave my mother somewhere about half of that six bob. Of course I went on with that until I was about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4095630\charrsid13830126 19 and a half }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3681841\charrsid13830126 you see.
